# Model Classes and Data Structures

## Overview

These rules govern the development of SwiftData models and data structures in Ora Browser. All models are located in the `ora/Models/` directory and follow SwiftData patterns for data persistence.

## Core Models

### 1. Tab Model (`Models/Tab.swift`)

**Purpose**: Represents individual browser tabs with WebKit integration

**Key Properties**:
- `id`: Unique identifier (UUID)
- `url`: Current URL (URL)
- `title`: Page title (String)
- `favicon`: Favicon URL (URL?)
- `container`: Parent container (TabContainer)
- `type`: Tab type (pinned, fav, normal)
- `isPrivate`: Private browsing flag (Bool)

**Transient Properties** (not persisted):
- `webView`: WKWebView instance
- `navigationDelegate`: WebViewNavigationDelegate
- `isWebViewReady`: Loading state
- `loadingProgress`: Progress indicator
- `historyManager`, `downloadManager`, `tabManager`: Service references

**Lifecycle**:
- Tabs are created through `TabManager.addTab()`
- WebView is initialized in `init()` with proper configuration
- State is managed through `WebViewNavigationDelegate`

### 2. TabContainer Model (`Models/TabContainer.swift`)

**Purpose**: Groups tabs into logical containers/spaces

**Key Properties**:
- `id`: Unique identifier (UUID)
- `name`: Container name (String)
- `emoji`: Container icon (String)
- `tabs`: Related tabs (Relationship)
- `lastAccessedAt`: Last access timestamp (Date?)

**Usage**:
- Manage tab organization
- Support container-specific settings
- Handle tab switching within containers

### 3. History Model (`Models/History.swift`)

**Purpose**: Store browsing history entries

**Key Properties**:
- `id`: Unique identifier (UUID)
- `url`: Visited URL (URL)
- `title`: Page title (String)
- `faviconURL`: Favicon URL (URL?)
- `faviconLocalFile`: Local favicon path (URL?)
- `visitedAt`: Visit timestamp (Date)
- `container`: Associated container (TabContainer)

**Features**:
- Automatic favicon download and storage
- Search and filtering capabilities
- Container-specific history tracking

### 4. Download Model (`Models/Download.swift`)

**Purpose**: Track file downloads

**Key Properties**:
- `id`: Unique identifier (UUID)
- `url`: Download URL (URL)
- `filename`: Target filename (String)
- `progress`: Download progress (Double)
- `status`: Download status (enum)
- `createdAt`: Creation timestamp (Date)

### 5. SearchEngine Model (`Models/SearchEngine.swift`)

**Purpose**: Define search engine configurations

**Key Properties**:
- `name`: Engine name (String)
- `color`: Brand color (Color)
- `icon`: Icon name (String)
- `aliases`: Command aliases (Array<String>)
- `searchURL`: Search URL template (String)
- `isAIChat`: AI chat flag (Bool)

## SwiftData Patterns

### 1. Model Definition
```swift
@Model
class Tab: ObservableObject, Identifiable {
    var id: UUID = UUID()
    var url: URL
    var title: String

    @Relationship(inverse: \TabContainer.tabs)
    var container: TabContainer

    init(url: URL, title: String, container: TabContainer) {
        self.url = url
        self.title = title
        self.container = container
    }
}
```

### 2. Relationships
- Use `@Relationship` for model relationships
- Define inverse relationships properly
- Handle relationship lifecycle

### 3. Queries
```swift
// Use @Query for reactive data fetching
@Query(sort: \Tab.lastAccessedAt, order: .reverse) var tabs: [Tab]

// Use FetchDescriptor for custom queries
let descriptor = FetchDescriptor<Tab>(
    predicate: #Predicate { $0.container.id == containerId }
)
let results = try modelContext.fetch(descriptor)
```

### 4. Model Context Usage
- Access context through `@Environment(\.modelContext)`
- Use context for insert, update, delete operations
- Handle save operations with error handling

## Data Persistence Rules

### 1. Private Browsing
- Use in-memory storage for private tabs
- Configure with `ModelConfiguration(isStoredInMemoryOnly: true)`
- Maintain isolation between private and normal data

### 2. Data Migration
- Handle model changes through SwiftData migrations
- Test migration scenarios thoroughly
- Provide fallback mechanisms

### 3. Error Handling
- Handle SwiftData context errors gracefully
- Implement retry mechanisms for failed operations
- Log errors for debugging

## Validation and Constraints

### 1. URL Validation
- Validate URLs before creating tabs
- Handle malformed URLs gracefully
- Sanitize user input

### 2. Data Integrity
- Maintain referential integrity between models
- Handle orphaned relationships
- Validate model constraints

### 3. State Consistency
- Ensure model state consistency
- Handle concurrent modifications
- Implement proper rollback mechanisms

## Performance Considerations

### 1. Query Optimization
- Use efficient predicates for filtering
- Sort data at the database level
- Minimize fetch operations

### 2. Memory Management
- Avoid loading unnecessary relationships
- Use lazy loading where appropriate
- Clean up unused model instances

### 3. Batch Operations
- Use batch operations for bulk updates
- Minimize context save operations
- Optimize for large datasets

## Testing

### 1. Model Testing
- Test model creation and validation
- Validate relationships and constraints
- Test data persistence and retrieval

### 2. Integration Testing
- Test model interactions with services
- Validate data flow between components
- Test migration scenarios

### 3. Performance Testing
- Test query performance with large datasets
- Validate memory usage patterns
- Test concurrent access scenarios

## Common Patterns

### 1. Tab Creation
```swift
let newTab = Tab(
    url: URL(string: "https://example.com")!,
    title: "Example",
    container: container,
    type: .normal,
    historyManager: historyManager,
    tabManager: tabManager,
    isPrivate: false
)
modelContext.insert(newTab)
try modelContext.save()
```

### 2. Container Management
```swift
let container = TabContainer(name: "Work", emoji: "💼")
modelContext.insert(container)
activeContainer = container
try modelContext.save()
```

### 3. History Recording
```swift
func recordVisit(title: String, url: URL, container: TabContainer) {
    let history = History(
        title: title,
        url: url,
        container: container
    )
    modelContext.insert(history)
    try modelContext.save()
}
```

These rules ensure consistent, well-structured model development in the Ora Browser codebase.